00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:38.240
what is App.net?

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:41.360
DALTON CALDWELL: App.net
is a social platform.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.170
You have an identity as
a user that you create,

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:46.400
and once you have
that identity created,

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.280
you can log into a manner
of different applications

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:51.860
that have been built by
third party developers.

00:00:51.860 --> 00:00:54.640
BRETT SLATKIN: OK, and so
that's from the consumer

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:55.265
side of things.

00:00:55.265 --> 00:00:55.620
DALTON CALDWELL: Sure.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:57.328
BRETT SLATKIN: What
about as a developer?

00:00:57.328 --> 00:00:59.005
What is App.net for developers?

00:00:59.005 --> 00:01:00.630
DALTON CALDWELL:
App.net for developers

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:02.310
is a social platform.

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:04.360
So if you go look at
our API documentation,

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:08.320
it looks a lot like what you've
seen with other social APIs,

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.840
like a Facebook or a Twitter.

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:13.970
Additionally, there's a bit more
in terms of file persistence

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:16.960
and key value stores
and things like that,

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:19.770
so it's almost like a
platform as a service.

00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:22.470
So call it a summation
of a platform

00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:23.842
as a service and a social API.

00:01:23.842 --> 00:01:25.550
That's what it looks
like to a developer.

00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:26.508
BRETT SLATKIN: Got you.

00:01:26.508 --> 00:01:30.100
And how is it different
than, say, Twitter, Facebook,

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:31.852
or Google+ and the
APIs they provide?

00:01:31.852 --> 00:01:33.560
I mean, that's social
infrastructure too.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:36.480
They have login and
messages and buttons

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:37.605
and all that kind of stuff.

00:01:37.605 --> 00:01:40.550
What makes App.net different
than what else is out there?

00:01:40.550 --> 00:01:42.520
DALTON CALDWELL:
We approach this

00:01:42.520 --> 00:01:43.972
from a conceptual perspective.

00:01:43.972 --> 00:01:44.930
Let me talk about that.

00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:45.763
BRETT SLATKIN: Yeah.

00:01:45.763 --> 00:01:48.490
DALTON CALDWELL: The issue with
existing social infrastructure

00:01:48.490 --> 00:01:51.970
is those are all
ad-supported services.

00:01:51.970 --> 00:01:55.440
And so the companies
that provide those APIs

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.680
are really focused on trying
to get users in a situation

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:02.974
where they can display ads
and target ads, which is fair.

00:02:02.974 --> 00:02:03.640
It's a business.

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:05.490
It's a good business.

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.540
I guess that's Google business.

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:10.240
And therefore, if you're
a third party developer,

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:12.110
there's a number of
encumbrances that you

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:14.900
tend to run up into
if the eyeballs start

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:16.920
going to your
application that's using

00:02:16.920 --> 00:02:18.900
the data of that
social platform.

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.730
And so we don't need to
enumerate all the ways

00:02:21.730 --> 00:02:23.832
that you can kind
of run into trouble.

00:02:23.832 --> 00:02:25.290
The difference with
App.net is it's

00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:28.392
made to look like infrastructure
and feel like infrastructure,

00:02:28.392 --> 00:02:29.850
so the business
model is a lot more

00:02:29.850 --> 00:02:33.040
like Dropbox or Evernote or
GitHub, where its freemium.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:34.750
There is a free
tier for consumers,

00:02:34.750 --> 00:02:38.970
but there's a paid tier as
well for consumer power users.

00:02:38.970 --> 00:02:41.530
And the idea here is that
the more applications

00:02:41.530 --> 00:02:45.180
that third party developers
build, the more attractive

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:47.820
the platform is to consumers,
and the more likely

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:49.770
we are to make more money.

00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:53.360
And therefore, we
are financially

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:55.960
incentivized to have as
many third party apps built

00:02:55.960 --> 00:02:59.370
as possible, to identify
as many niches as possible,

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:02.320
to expand the value of
the platform instead of,

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:04.020
oh, yeah, I guess
we have an API.

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:06.270
I hope people don't
use it too much.

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:08.010
We want our first
party app, which

00:03:08.010 --> 00:03:10.630
is what's serving
all the advertising,

00:03:10.630 --> 00:03:12.190
to be what people
interface with.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:15.165
And so from a business
model perspective,

00:03:15.165 --> 00:03:16.540
that's what's
different about it.

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:19.081
And so it's caused us to make
a number of different decisions

00:03:19.081 --> 00:03:21.170
in the API itself, and in
our relationship for how

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:22.575
third parties integrate with it.

00:03:22.575 --> 00:03:24.750
BRETT SLATKIN: That
makes a lot of sense.

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:28.260
So that sounds like the value
of App.net to a developer,

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:30.100
and so presumably
there's a bunch

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.550
of developers using App.net
to build their products.

00:03:32.550 --> 00:03:35.047
I thought maybe you could step
us through or explain to us

00:03:35.047 --> 00:03:36.880
some of the apps out
there that are building

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:38.614
on top of App.net's social API.

00:03:38.614 --> 00:03:39.530
DALTON CALDWELL: Sure.

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:42.745
So there's a number of
different verticals,

00:03:42.745 --> 00:03:43.620
I guess, is one way--

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:45.080
BRETT SLATKIN: Oh, why don't
we start with Passport, though.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:46.288
So Passport's your app, yeah.

00:03:46.288 --> 00:03:49.159
So what is Passport, and what
does Passport do for the user?

00:03:49.159 --> 00:03:51.200
DALTON CALDWELL: So we do
have a first party app.

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:52.540
It's called Passport.

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:56.180
Right now, it's live on
iOS and Android both,

00:03:56.180 --> 00:03:59.250
and the advantage of Passport,
if you have it installed,

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:02.932
is you can do single
sign-on to any App.net app

00:04:02.932 --> 00:04:04.295
on that platform.

00:04:04.295 --> 00:04:05.920
So if you're a third
party dev, and you

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:09.849
launch the menu that
integrates with App.net,

00:04:09.849 --> 00:04:11.640
the user will be able
to do single sign-on.

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:13.430
Additionally,
there's a directory

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:17.250
of all the applications
on that platform,

00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:19.519
so users can easily
discover your application

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:21.110
if you integrate with us.

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:22.130
And so the user goes in.

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:23.380
They can manage their account.

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:24.690
They can change their settings.

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:27.273
They can see what applications
they can do single sign-on are.

00:04:27.273 --> 00:04:30.066
They can be prompted to download
that application to the device,

00:04:30.066 --> 00:04:31.190
and then do single sign-on.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:32.630
Bam, they're in.

00:04:32.630 --> 00:04:34.870
So it's a really smooth
user experience for users.

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:37.020
And again, the idea of
having this platform exist,

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:42.270
of having Passport exist, is to
streamline the user experience

00:04:42.270 --> 00:04:44.380
for any third party dev
that builds a new app.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:45.622
BRETT SLATKIN: Got you.

00:04:45.622 --> 00:04:47.580
OK, so now I've installed
Passport on my phone.

00:04:47.580 --> 00:04:50.082
I go in there as a
discovery platform.

00:04:50.082 --> 00:04:51.040
I find a bunch of apps.

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:52.220
I install them.

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:54.800
So what are some the apps that
users are using out there?

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:55.960
You said verticals.

00:04:55.960 --> 00:04:58.440
DALTON CALDWELL: Yeah, so one
of them is micro blogging.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:00.782
And so that's something like
a Twitter like experience

00:05:00.782 --> 00:05:02.490
or a Facebook news
feed experience, where

00:05:02.490 --> 00:05:04.730
you put public
status updates there,

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:07.010
and people can reply
to them and all that.

00:05:07.010 --> 00:05:09.060
The most notable application
in that vertical--

00:05:09.060 --> 00:05:13.200
one of them is called Riposte,
R-I-P-O-S-T-E, on iOS.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:14.640
There's also Felix.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:15.847
There's also NetBot.

00:05:15.847 --> 00:05:17.430
Those have all been
featured by Apple.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:19.230
These aren't just little toys.

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:23.570
These are good enough for Apple
editorial to feature them.

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:26.850
On Android, I think Robin is
definitely the most famous

00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:29.920
of those micro blogging
style services.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:30.880
BRETT SLATKIN: Got you.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:32.180
DALTON CALDWELL: So
that's app vertical.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:34.140
BRETT SLATKIN: And then, so
the other ones were, I saw,

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:35.440
photo sharing's
another vertical.

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:37.170
DALTON CALDWELL: Yeah, there's
photo sharing applications.

00:05:37.170 --> 00:05:38.711
Again, you can use
the infrastructure

00:05:38.711 --> 00:05:41.530
to build a full photo-only
feed to post photos.

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:43.877
Because we have
file persistence,

00:05:43.877 --> 00:05:46.210
the files that are updated
are stored in the user's file

00:05:46.210 --> 00:05:48.570
bucket, so users can still
own their own content.

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:52.480
And so there's Climber
and Sprinter on iOS side.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:55.112
And I don't think there's a
pure play Android photo client.

00:05:55.112 --> 00:05:56.070
BRETT SLATKIN: Not yet.

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:56.855
DALTON CALDWELL: But
someone should build that.

00:05:56.855 --> 00:05:57.200
BRETT SLATKIN: Someone
should build that.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:58.770
Sounds good.

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.690
And then the other thing,
strong part of App.net

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:03.430
is kind of messaging
and group messaging.

00:06:03.430 --> 00:06:05.240
So what are some of the
apps that are doing that?

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:06.700
DALTON CALDWELL: From a
developer's perspective,

00:06:06.700 --> 00:06:09.475
in addition to the public post
API, that's what it's called,

00:06:09.475 --> 00:06:13.350
there's something called
the channels/messages API.

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:15.430
And the idea from
that is you can

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:18.990
send private or
non-private messages

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:20.740
to a selected group
of people, rather than

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:22.050
posting it to your feed.

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:25.050
And from this, you can
build what's basically

00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:28.930
group messaging apps, so
imagine WhatsApp or Kik

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:31.650
or something like that.

00:06:31.650 --> 00:06:34.790
Any third party developer can
use App.net's infrastructure

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:37.380
to build their own group
messaging application,

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:40.560
and all of the back-end
is taken care of.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:42.410
And we actively
embrace and want people

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:45.134
to build these as opposed to
having unofficial APIs, which

00:06:45.134 --> 00:06:47.050
is different than some
of those other services

00:06:47.050 --> 00:06:48.430
I just mentioned.

00:06:48.430 --> 00:06:52.240
And so if you want to build a
new UI paradigm for doing group

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:56.012
messaging or doing group photo
messaging or you name it,

00:06:56.012 --> 00:06:56.720
people can do it.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:58.610
So the most popular
in that vertical right

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:04.440
now is something called Whisper
on iOS, and it's got stickers.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:04.940
Yeah.

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:05.280
BRETT SLATKIN: Like Path.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:05.620
Right?

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:08.210
DALTON CALDWELL: Yeah, exactly,
it's a lot like Path, actually,

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:09.084
so it's got stickers.

00:07:09.084 --> 00:07:11.310
You can broadcast your
location to friends.

00:07:11.310 --> 00:07:12.920
You can do check-ins
with friends

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:14.530
because we have a location API.

00:07:14.530 --> 00:07:17.485
And again, it interoperates
with any other App.net app.

00:07:17.485 --> 00:07:19.110
So if an Android
developer, say, wanted

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:21.410
to build a group
messaging application,

00:07:21.410 --> 00:07:23.160
anyone using Whisper
would be able to talk

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:24.760
to people using their
application, which

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:25.384
is pretty cool.

00:07:25.384 --> 00:07:27.080
So given how popular
group messaging is,

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:29.413
I think there's a lot of
opportunity for developers that

00:07:29.413 --> 00:07:31.570
want to build group
messaging applications.

00:07:31.570 --> 00:07:32.550
BRETT SLATKIN: Great.

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:34.440
So let's move on.

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:37.534
I think that you've shown some
examples of these great apps,

00:07:37.534 --> 00:07:39.950
and we've talked a little bit
about the particulars of why

00:07:39.950 --> 00:07:41.460
developers choose
to use App.net.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:43.810
I wanted to get into the
nitty-gritty of the APIs

00:07:43.810 --> 00:07:44.310
themselves.

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:46.070
You mentioned a little bit
about channels and the file

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:47.790
persistency API,
and that's great.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:51.240
But I think that,
as a developer,

00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:55.602
I'm considering using App.net,
and when I think about that,

00:07:55.602 --> 00:07:57.310
I say, well, what is
it going to save me?

00:07:57.310 --> 00:07:58.780
What do I not have
to do anymore?

00:07:58.780 --> 00:08:02.140
If I choose to use App.net,
where am I starting?

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:04.214
What's the value that I
get from using your APIs?

00:08:04.214 --> 00:08:05.130
DALTON CALDWELL: Sure.

00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:07.046
Well, let's talk about
it from the perspective

00:08:07.046 --> 00:08:08.470
of, say, a client developer.

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:10.750
If you're an iOS or Android
developer, right out

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.630
of the gate, there's extremely
high quality, open source,

00:08:13.630 --> 00:08:18.800
SDKs that wrap all of
our infrastructure,

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.530
so you just drag that right into
your respective text editor.

00:08:22.530 --> 00:08:27.020
So you get authentication,
so it uses OAuth.

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:29.470
And also, you'll get the
single sign-on from Passport.

00:08:29.470 --> 00:08:32.250
So authentication is simple.

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:34.610
You get Social
Graph, too, once you

00:08:34.610 --> 00:08:35.860
have a user identity set up.

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:38.123
Follows, following,
recommendations,

00:08:38.123 --> 00:08:39.539
all that good stuff
that you would

00:08:39.539 --> 00:08:42.270
get from a standard social API,
you get right out of the box,

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:44.087
so you don't have the
blank app problem.

00:08:44.087 --> 00:08:45.920
That's pretty scary
when you're a developer.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.080
And maybe you get all the
technical infrastructure

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.810
working, but you have
a blank database.

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:52.365
That's not a-- we've
all been there.

00:08:52.365 --> 00:08:52.865
Right?

00:08:52.865 --> 00:08:53.940
BRETT SLATKIN: Yeah, this
is the new app problem.

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:54.560
You get a new app.

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:54.905
You install it.

00:08:54.905 --> 00:08:55.800
You don't have any friends.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.380
You have to send out
emails or something.

00:08:57.380 --> 00:08:58.060
DALTON CALDWELL:
It's pretty tough.

00:08:58.060 --> 00:08:58.400
Right?

00:08:58.400 --> 00:08:58.770
BRETT SLATKIN: Right.

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:00.369
So as a developer,
I spend all my time

00:09:00.369 --> 00:09:01.910
trying to just get
people in the door

00:09:01.910 --> 00:09:03.868
as opposed to focusing
on the actual experience

00:09:03.868 --> 00:09:06.022
that I want to provide to users.

00:09:06.022 --> 00:09:07.480
DALTON CALDWELL:
And that's exactly

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:08.896
the reason I think
the world needs

00:09:08.896 --> 00:09:12.320
this kind of infrastructure, is
that users should have the best

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.230
apps that serve their needs
and choose between those,

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:17.750
as opposed to, oh, this
app has all the network

00:09:17.750 --> 00:09:20.460
effects, this one company, even
though their products aren't

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:21.220
quite as good.

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:23.240
And there's all these
really talented designers

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:25.610
or talented innovative
UIs being built,

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:27.810
but because they can't tap
into the large user base,

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:28.730
they're just going
to get squashed.

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:29.780
I think that's a shame.

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:30.790
I don't think it's
good for users.

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:31.870
BRETT SLATKIN: Right.

