for all the major languages
that are out here.

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:39.560
I saw that.

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:43.210
And then like a RESTful API and
the Cores API for JavaScript

00:09:43.210 --> 00:09:45.850
and the browsers,
so cross domain.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.632
In terms of like the
nitty-gritty specifics-- so

00:09:48.632 --> 00:09:50.132
maybe I can round
these off, and you

00:09:50.132 --> 00:09:51.130
can tell me what each
one of them does.

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:53.290
So there's an account
and authentication APIs.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:54.860
We talked about Password
and single sign-on.

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:55.310
DALTON CALDWELL: Yes.

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:56.675
BRETT SLATKIN: I also know
there's a two-factor thing that

00:09:56.675 --> 00:09:57.130
you guys--

00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:58.430
DALTON CALDWELL: Yeah, we
have two-factor factor off,

00:09:58.430 --> 00:10:00.660
so without you the developer
having to do anything,

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:02.960
two-factor off on your
App.net account just works.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:05.420
And it uses the
standard standards,

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:08.317
so Google Authenticator,
all the-- what is that, OTA?

00:10:08.317 --> 00:10:09.650
What's the name of the standard?

00:10:09.650 --> 00:10:10.194
BRETT SLATKIN: OTP, yeah.

00:10:10.194 --> 00:10:11.777
DALTON CALDWELL:
OTP, that just works.

00:10:11.777 --> 00:10:14.220
So any user with
an App.net account,

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:16.335
if they want to turn
on 2FA, they got it.

00:10:16.335 --> 00:10:18.293
BRETT SLATKIN: Yeah, and
that's important to me

00:10:18.293 --> 00:10:19.740
because I feel
like I don't trust

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:21.031
other people with my passwords.

00:10:21.031 --> 00:10:22.830
I'm always very
worried about that.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:24.580
So when I install a
new app, I'm thinking,

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:26.538
OK, well, I have to make
up a password for them

00:10:26.538 --> 00:10:28.730
because they probably aren't
managing it correctly,

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:29.813
and that worries me a lot.

00:10:29.813 --> 00:10:32.720
And so it seems like, just
from a user's perspective,

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:34.710
I like that more that
I can trust maybe

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:36.220
App.net in the same
way that I trust

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:38.000
Google with my single sign-on.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:38.450
DALTON CALDWELL: Correct.

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:40.340
BRETT SLATKIN: That's great,
but you guys are providing that.

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:41.965
DALTON CALDWELL:
Yeah, so the developer

00:10:41.965 --> 00:10:44.196
doesn't have to do anything,
and 2FA just works.

00:10:44.196 --> 00:10:45.070
BRETT SLATKIN: Great.

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:47.920
And then the other one I saw
was the user streams API,

00:10:47.920 --> 00:10:49.260
and that's really interesting.

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:50.520
What does that do
for developers?

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:52.061
DALTON CALDWELL: So
the streaming API

00:10:52.061 --> 00:10:53.310
is quite powerful.

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:56.024
Basically, you get call backs
when different events happen,

00:10:56.024 --> 00:10:57.440
and so you can get
call backs when

00:10:57.440 --> 00:10:59.956
things in the global
stream happen.

00:10:59.956 --> 00:11:01.830
For the user streaming
API, you get call back

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:04.790
events when something
happens on a user's object,

00:11:04.790 --> 00:11:09.140
so if they star something,
if they follow someone,

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:11.680
if a channel that they're
in-- it's like a group chat.

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:13.830
Like if you ran
group chat client,

00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:17.350
you can have it be very
performant by actually getting

00:11:17.350 --> 00:11:19.830
streams back instead of having
to poll it for new messages.

00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:21.621
BRETT SLATKIN: And this
is into the browser

00:11:21.621 --> 00:11:24.090
or into the clients, or where
do I get the user streams?

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:26.465
DALTON CALDWELL: It depends
on what library you're using.

00:11:26.465 --> 00:11:29.402
I mean, if you're using
that iOS SDK, you've got it.

00:11:29.402 --> 00:11:31.860
BRETT SLATKIN: So it'll push
right down to the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:32.550
Yeah.

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:33.950
DALTON CALDWELL: It
works out of the box.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:36.116
BRETT SLATKIN: One of the
things that most interests

00:11:36.116 --> 00:11:37.940
me about App.net that
I want to talk about

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:42.210
was how you guys support
open standards and all

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:43.030
the open formats.

00:11:43.030 --> 00:11:44.840
I was going to go through
the list of all the things

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:46.400
that you support because
it's a laundry list, which

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:47.840
is really impressive.

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:51.435
So RSS, really simple
syndication feeds, activity

00:11:51.435 --> 00:11:53.560
streams which are kind of
a social version of that.

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:56.472
You support both, I think,
the XML and JSON versions

00:11:56.472 --> 00:11:58.680
of that, which I think nobody
else actually supports,

00:11:58.680 --> 00:11:59.675
which is interesting.

00:11:59.675 --> 00:12:02.050
PubSubHubbub, which is something
I worked on, which makes

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:04.210
feeds real time, which
is great, WebFinger

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:06.930
for decentralized discovery.

00:12:06.930 --> 00:12:09.560
You have microformats built
into all the different pages,

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:10.790
profile pages.

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:13.670
You support Media
RSS and Geo RSS,

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:16.580
and then you also support
IndieAuth and the rel-me auth

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:19.390
through some of the link
relations on sites you have.

00:12:19.390 --> 00:12:22.332
So you can interoperate
with almost all

00:12:22.332 --> 00:12:24.290
the open standards that
are out there that I've

00:12:24.290 --> 00:12:27.420
heard of that actually
have any kind of usage.

00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:29.610
That's awesome, but
why did you do it?

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:32.380
What's the value in
providing open standards

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:33.957
for App.net users
and developers?

00:12:33.957 --> 00:12:35.790
DALTON CALDWELL: We're
doing it because it's

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.020
entirely consistent
with why we're here.

00:12:38.020 --> 00:12:41.110
The goal of App.net is to
be a really useful platform

00:12:41.110 --> 00:12:41.820
for users.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:44.892
And the more existing
data, the more ways

00:12:44.892 --> 00:12:47.350
that it can interoperate with
other things in the workflow,

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:50.070
the more valuable we
become to end users

00:12:50.070 --> 00:12:51.280
as well as to developers.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.850
So to just be really
concrete, on the RSS case,

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:56.380
we built an open source thing
called PourOver-- it also

00:12:56.380 --> 00:12:59.520
supports PubSubHubbub-- that
made it really, really simple

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:03.420
for any RSS feed to
get ported into posts.

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:04.650
That was nice.

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:05.820
We supported open standards.

00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:07.990
It was open source, so you
can go find it on GitHub.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:09.640
But it also provided
tremendous value

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:11.650
for the users and
developers of App.net

00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:16.440
because a whole lot of RSS
feed started pouring in,

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.190
which made the service
more viable for end users

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:20.090
and for developers.

00:13:20.090 --> 00:13:23.530
And so we're doing it because
it's consistent with our goals,

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:26.000
our mission, as well as
our business model, which

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.212
is going into the workflow
as much as possible.

00:13:29.212 --> 00:13:30.920
BRETT SLATKIN: And
how does that contrast

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:32.490
to some of the other
companies out there that

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:33.864
aren't supporting
open standards.

00:13:33.864 --> 00:13:36.550
I think we talk
about them a lot,

00:13:36.550 --> 00:13:39.980
but even Twitter has reduced
the number of RSS feeds.

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:43.200
Google+ still has
no RSS feeds at all.

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:44.660
What's the contrast there?

00:13:44.660 --> 00:13:46.390
It's in line with
your principles,

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:51.010
but at the end of the day,
why isn't everyone adopting

00:13:51.010 --> 00:13:52.187
open standards like you are?

00:13:52.187 --> 00:13:54.770
DALTON CALDWELL: I think it has
to come down to business model

00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:56.769
motivations, like I know
many of the people that

00:13:56.769 --> 00:13:59.196
work at those other companies,
and I respect them deeply,

00:13:59.196 --> 00:14:00.570
and I've learned
a lot from them.

00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:03.029
And when you talk to them,
especially behind closed doors,

00:14:03.029 --> 00:14:05.070
they admit that it's
difficult to make a business

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:08.160
case for supporting
many of these standards.

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:11.110
They're not necessarily widely
adopted by their user base.

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:13.920
And if you have
100 million users,

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:18.370
and your business is to throw
as many interruptive ads

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:20.910
as you can at people inside
of a first party client,

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:22.660
it's really hard to
make a business case

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:26.010
for developing and supporting
those particular open

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:27.010
standards.

00:14:27.010 --> 00:14:28.946
And in our case, we're
not doing this, again,

00:14:28.946 --> 00:14:30.320
because we think
it's going to be

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:33.380
great to appeal to people
and then in six months,

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:35.450
change our mind and
deprecate all this stuff.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:38.160
This is really entirely
consistent with our business

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:40.700
value, which is
just having as much

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:43.380
content flow-in and content
flow-out as possible,

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:46.800
to be pipes for more and more
apps to be developed on it.

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:49.900
And so I think it's the business
case argument that, really, we

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.069
can tie this stuff back to.

00:14:52.069 --> 00:14:53.985
And I'd love to know if
you agree or disagree.

00:14:53.985 --> 00:14:55.630
BRETT SLATKIN: No, that
makes perfect sense to me.

00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:56.930
I just want to highlight that.

00:14:56.930 --> 00:14:57.350
DALTON CALDWELL: Yeah, I know.

00:14:57.350 --> 00:14:59.390
I mean, like I said, I've
talked to many people

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:00.181
at those companies.

00:15:00.181 --> 00:15:03.000
And it's very difficult
to make a business case

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.890
to senior management about
why some of those standards

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:10.090
are going to move the
needle in a financial sense.

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:11.530
BRETT SLATKIN: Yeah.

00:15:11.530 --> 00:15:14.609
So you recently celebrated
a year of App.net,

00:15:14.609 --> 00:15:15.400
so congratulations.

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:15.490
DALTON CALDWELL: Thanks.

00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:16.770
BRETT SLATKIN: That's great.

00:15:16.770 --> 00:15:18.270
So we've gone over
a ton of features

00:15:18.270 --> 00:15:21.080
already that have
either been at launch

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:23.715
or been launched
since then, but what

00:15:23.715 --> 00:15:25.090
are some of the
other things that

00:15:25.090 --> 00:15:27.220
have changed over the
last year of App.net?

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:28.690
DALTON CALDWELL: Well, I
think the most important thing

00:15:28.690 --> 00:15:31.370
from a consumer perspective
is we added the free tier.

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:33.020
We did not have a
free tier at first

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:36.090
because the service,
essentially, didn't exist.

00:15:36.090 --> 00:15:38.720
And so it was very rough, and we
didn't want a lot of consumers

00:15:38.720 --> 00:15:41.260
to sign up for a service
that's all about third party

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:43.110
apps with no third party apps.

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:46.270
That's definitely the oxymoron
of all time, right there.

00:15:46.270 --> 00:15:50.230
So we gave developers the API.

00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:52.511
They built a bunch of stuff.

00:15:52.511 --> 00:15:53.510
It's quite high quality.

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:54.490
They iterated on it.

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:56.115
Then we launched the
free tier to start

00:15:56.115 --> 00:15:57.580
working on user distribution.

00:15:57.580 --> 00:16:00.570
Additionally, we built out the
channels API and the files API.

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:02.069
Many of the things
we just mentioned

00:16:02.069 --> 00:16:05.740
were launched not at day
one, but every month or two,

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:07.781
we added more and more things.

00:16:07.781 --> 00:16:09.530
And then finally, the
most important thing

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:12.300
we've been working on is out of
the box experience and new user

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:13.690
experience.

00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:16.310
We realize that, for this to be
very valuable for developers,

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:18.075
we need lots and lots
and lots of users.

00:16:18.075 --> 00:16:20.700
And we need to make it seamless
so that if you build an App.net

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:24.274
app, the users can sign up
and create an account, that

00:16:24.274 --> 00:16:25.940
don't already have
one, without it being

00:16:25.940 --> 00:16:28.880
this complicated,
laborious, painful process.

00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:31.460
So we've been really optimizing
our flows and our marking in

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:36.090
and the power of our engine
to drive people to sign up

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:38.610
so that the whole ecosystem
can benefit from that.

00:16:38.610 --> 00:16:40.110
And so we've been
spending, frankly,

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:42.292
a lot of cycles on that
out of the box experience.

00:16:42.292 --> 00:16:44.250
That's why we built
Passport, because we wanted

00:16:44.250 --> 00:16:45.624
to make it really
simple and have

00:16:45.624 --> 00:16:47.970
a great experience for just
normal users that aren't

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:52.380
technical, that don't care
about APIs, just to be like,

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:54.460
oh, someone launched a
new group messaging app.

00:16:54.460 --> 00:16:55.540
I want to try this out.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:57.490
Oh, click, click,
click, they're in.

00:16:57.490 --> 00:16:59.740
We've got to get that right
for this to be successful,

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:01.282
so we've been focusing
on that a lot.

00:17:01.282 --> 00:17:02.698
BRETT SLATKIN: The
other one I saw

00:17:02.698 --> 00:17:04.422
that you launched
over the past year

00:17:04.422 --> 00:17:05.599
was the developer incentive.

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:06.140
DALTON CALDWELL:
Oh, that's right.

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:08.181
BRETT SLATKIN: So what is
the developer-- I mean,

00:17:08.181 --> 00:17:09.040
that sounds awesome.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:09.581
What is that?

00:17:09.581 --> 00:17:10.797
What does it mean?

00:17:10.797 --> 00:17:11.380
What do I get?

00:17:11.380 --> 00:17:13.921
DALTON CALDWELL: Sure, well,
the developer incentive program,

00:17:13.921 --> 00:17:17.420
we're paying out $30,000 per
month, no strings attached.

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:19.079
It's not an investment
or anything.

00:17:19.079 --> 00:17:22.349
It's just a check to
the developers that

00:17:22.349 --> 00:17:25.919
build applications that
provide most value to users.

00:17:25.919 --> 00:17:28.210
And so the idea is that's a
pool of money that goes out

00:17:28.210 --> 00:17:30.690
every month, and it gets
sliced and diced to go

00:17:30.690 --> 00:17:32.690
to different developers
in the incentive program

00:17:32.690 --> 00:17:36.380
depending on how users
rate their apps for how

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:37.692
much utility they get from it.

00:17:37.692 --> 00:17:38.900
So you can't game the system.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:41.420
You can't show up and
build some crappy port

00:17:41.420 --> 00:17:44.230
and throw it in the store and
expect to make money from it.

00:17:44.230 --> 00:17:46.350
People have to actually
use it and like it.

00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:48.542
But if you build something
that people use and like,

00:17:48.542 --> 00:17:50.500
it means you're going to
have an income stream.

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:53.610
And we did this to help
solve the cold start problem.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:54.700
We know we're brand new.

00:17:54.700 --> 00:17:57.210
We know we aren't the size of
some of these other platforms,

00:17:57.210 --> 00:18:01.520
but this gives you a huge
leg up out of the gate

00:18:01.520 --> 00:18:06.380
to make this worth your
while, worth a shot

00:18:06.380 --> 00:18:07.677
to build application staging.

00:18:07.677 --> 00:18:09.010
Frankly, it's worked quite well.

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:09.670
BRETT SLATKIN: What
are you looking forward

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:11.124
to in the next year of App.net?

00:18:11.124 --> 00:18:12.040
DALTON CALDWELL: Sure.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.210
So we're really focusing
on new user experience,

00:18:15.210 --> 00:18:17.290
out of the box experience.

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:19.960
There's just over
160,000 users right now

00:18:19.960 --> 00:18:23.060
as we're recording this,
which is a really solid place

00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:23.680
to be at.

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:26.419
It's much bigger than a
lot of companies make it.

00:18:26.419 --> 00:18:27.960
But we're really
focused on what it's

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:30.990
going to take to get an order
of magnitude more usage out

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:33.160
of the thing and to
take those channels,

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:35.560
and so that's a really
important piece.

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:38.074
Additionally, developers,
now that all the

00:18:38.074 --> 00:18:39.490
Hello, World stuff
has been built,

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:41.770
and now we have high level
APIs that have been built,

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:44.290
and there's all these
verticals have been populated,

00:18:44.290 --> 00:18:47.540
we're supporting developers
that are building more rich,

00:18:47.540 --> 00:18:51.350
deep apps that are
pushing the limits of what

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:52.790
you can do with a social API.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:56.329
It's, again, what I think the
benefit of our business model

00:18:56.329 --> 00:18:58.870
is, is that we want developers
to push the limits of what you

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:03.090
can do instead of the
lowest common denominator.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:04.565
Like do you know
when a startup is

00:19:04.565 --> 00:19:06.450
on its-- they innovate,
innovative, innovate,

00:19:06.450 --> 00:19:08.380
and then when you get
to a certain size,

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:10.485
most of your innovation is like
new ad targeting and things.

00:19:10.485 --> 00:19:11.650
BRETT SLATKIN: Yeah, you're
like this is good enough.

00:19:11.650 --> 00:19:12.250
This works in our system.

